<!--- 
    Vert.x-Web is configured by using configuration stores to define settings that are then
    loaded into the application using a ConfigRetriever. This allows for flexible configuration 
    options, including loading from files, the event bus, or even directly from xml.
-->
<!ELEMENT vertx-web (context-listener|context-params|verticles)*>

<!--- Optional context listener for Vert.x -->
<!ELEMENT context-listener EMPTY>

<!---
    Tuning parameters for the Vert.x instance.
 -->
<!ELEMENT context-params (blocked-thread-check-interval|event-loop-pool-size|warning-exception-time|disable-tccl|worker-pool-size|max-event-loop-execute-time|max-worker-execute-time|error-handler|internal-blocking-pool-size|event-bus-options|prefer-native-transport|metric-class|cluster-manager|ha-enabled|address-resolver-options|quorum-size|ha-group|metrics-options|tracing-options|use-daemon-thread|file-system-options)*>

<!---
    The default event loop pool size is twice the number of cores on the machine.
    You can override the value by specifying a number here. E.g., 2, 4, etc.
-->
<!ELEMENT event-loop-pool-size (#PCDATA)>

<!---
    An alternative way to run blocking code is to use a worker verticle. A worker
    verticle is always executed with a thread from the worker pool. By default 
    blocking code is executed on the Vert.x worker pool, configured with worker-pool-size.
-->
<!ELEMENT worker-pool-size (#PCDATA)>

<!---
    The default value of blocked thread check interval = 1000 ms.
    You can override the value by specifying the below paraeter.
-->
<!ELEMENT blocked-thread-check-interval (#PCDATA)>

<!---
    Configure the maximum time an event loop can be blocked, which is useful for preventing
    long-running blocking operations from impacting the system's performance.
    This is typically set using the VertxOptions class. The default value for the maximum event
    loop execution time is 2 seconds.
-->
<!ELEMENT max-event-loop-execute-time (#PCDATA)>

<!---
    Setting dictates the maximum amount of time a worker thread can be blocked before being
    interrupted. By default, this is set to 60 seconds. This setting helps prevent blocking 
    worker threads from impacting other verticles or event loops. 
-->
<!ELEMENT max-worker-execute-time (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    Vert.x is designed to be non-blocking, meaning it uses an event loop to handle asynchronous
    operations. However, some tasks are inherently blocking (e.g., waiting for a file to be read,
    waiting for a database query to complete). The internal blocking pool provides a thread pool
    for handling these blocking operations without blocking the event loop.
-->
<!ELEMENT internal-blocking-pool-size (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    In Vert.x a cluster manager is used for various functions including:
    1. Discovery and group membership of Vert.x nodes in a cluster
    2. Maintaining cluster wide topic subscriber lists (so we know which nodes are interested in which event bus addresses)
    3. Distributed Map support
    4. Distributed Locks
    5. Distributed Counters

Cluster managers do not handle the event bus inter-node transport, this is done directly by Vert.x with TCP connections.
-->
<!ELEMENT cluster-manager EMPTY>

<!--- 
    High Availability (HA) is enabled through this configuration, specifically by setting the HA
    property to true. This ensures that your Verticles and other core components are deployed across
    a cluster of Vert.x nodes, providing resilience against node failures. When HA is enabled, 
    Vert.x will automatically re-deploy affected Verticles to other healthy nodes in the cluster
    if a node fails, ensuring continuous application operation.
-->
<!ELEMENT ha-enabled (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    The quorum size refers to the minimum number of nodes required in a cluster to maintain a quorum
    for operations like HA (High Availability) and distributed data consistency. It's crucial for 
    ensuring that the cluster remains operational and that data is appropriately replicated even if
    some nodes fail.
-->
<!ELEMENT quorum-size (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    Set the high availability group name.
-->
<!ELEMENT ha-group (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It provides configuration options for how Vert.x interacts with the file system. 
    Key options include enabling class path resolving, setting a file cache directory for 
    improved performance, and controlling file caching for classpath resources.
-->
<!ELEMENT file-system-options (class-path-resolving-enabled|file-caching-enabled|file-cache-dir)*>

<!--- 
    When set, Vert.x will attempt to load files from the classpath if they are not found on the 
    filesystem. This is useful for applications that package resources directly within the 
    application archive.
-->
<!ELEMENT class-path-resolving-enabled (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    If true, files accessed through the classpath will be cached on the filesystem, 
    even if classPathResolvingEnabled is false.
-->
<!ELEMENT file-caching-enabled (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    Specifies the directory where files from the classpath will be extracted and cached for 
    faster access. This can significantly improve IO performance when accessing files 
    packaged within the application.
-->
<!ELEMENT file-cache-dir (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    Vert.x uses a metrics SPI (Service Provider Interface) to provide metrics for various components
    like HTTP clients, servers, event bus, and pools. Micrometer and Dropwizard are examples of 
    metrics implementations that Vert.x supports. You can configure Vert.x to use a specific metrics 
    implementation and customize the metrics it collects, including enabling or disabling specific 
    labels for more granular data
-->
<!ELEMENT metrics-options (enabled|factory)*>

<!--- 
    Indicates whether metric collection is enabled.
-->
<!ELEMENT enabled (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    Factory class for creating metric instance.
-->
<!ELEMENT factory EMPTY>

<!--- 
    Used to configure distributed tracing behavior. They allow you to control how tracing is handled 
    across different components of your application, such as HTTP servers and clients. Key aspects 
    include the tracing policy (PROPAGATE, ALWAYS, or IGNORE), and the ability to create custom tracing 
    options through a VertxTracerFactory.
-->
<!ELEMENT tracing-options (factory)*>

<!--- 
    Factory class for creating standard tracer.
-->
<!ELEMENT factory EMPTY>

<!--- 
    This setting determines the threshold for triggering a stack trace when a thread is blocked. 
    By default, the blocking thread warning appears after 60 seconds. Setting a lower 
    warningExceptionTime value, such as 2 seconds, causes the warning to include a stack trace 
    whenever it's triggered, while a higher value might only display the warning without a stack trace.
-->
<!ELEMENT warning-exception-time (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    Set whether to prefer the native transport to the NIO transport.
-->
<!ELEMENT prefer-native-transport (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    The TCCL is a thread-local variable used to determine which classloader to use when loading 
    classes for a given thread.
    This will prevent Vert.x from setting the Context's classloader as the thread context classloader 
    on actions executed on that Context. While this can be a workaround for certain issues, it's 
    important to be aware of potential consequences, as it may affect security checks and other 
    aspects of the application's behavior. 
-->
<!ELEMENT disable-tccl (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    This setting will enable Vert.x to use daemon threads for Verticles, meaning they don't prevent 
    the JVM from exiting when they are no longer running. This is a design choice to ensure Vert.x 
    applications can be properly shutdown and resources are released even if Verticles are still running.
-->
<!ELEMENT use-daemon-thread (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It allows customization of the Vert.x Event Bus. It's used to configure the default behavior 
    of the event bus, which is a distributed messaging system within Vert.x.
-->
<!ELEMENT event-bus-options (cluster-public-host|cluster-public-port|cluster-ping-interval|cluster-ping-reply-interval|accept-backlog|reconnect-interval|reconnect-attempts|connect-timeout|trust-all|log-activity)*>

<!--- 
    The public host to advertise for clustering. If null, the same host as the cluster host will be used.
-->
<!ELEMENT cluster-public-host EMPTY>

<!--- 
    The public port to advertise for clustering. If -1, the same port as the cluster port will be used.
-->
<!ELEMENT cluster-public-port (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It refers to the frequency at which a node in a cluster checks for other cluster members. 
    The default value is 20,000 milliseconds (20 seconds). This setting determines how often a 
    node sends "ping" messages to other nodes in the cluster to confirm their presence and health.
-->
<!ELEMENT cluster-ping-interval (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It controls the timeout for receiving a reply after sending a ping message to other nodes 
    in a Vert.x cluster. This setting determines how long a node waits for a response before 
    it considers a node in the cluster to be dead. The default value is 20,000 milliseconds (20 seconds).
-->
<!ELEMENT cluster-ping-reply-interval (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    Setting for the Event Bus determines how many pending client connections can be queued when 
    the Event Bus is busy. The default value is 1024. This setting is part of the EventBusOptions 
    and can be adjusted to fit specific application needs.
-->
<!ELEMENT accept-backlog (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It configures how long the Event Bus waits before attempting to reconnect after a connection 
    failure. This setting is crucial for ensuring reliable communication, especially in scenarios
    where network connectivity might be intermittent. The default value is 50 milliseconds.
-->
<!ELEMENT reconnect-interval (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    In Vert.x, the EventBus offers automatic reconnection attempts after a disconnection. 
    You can configure the reconnection behavior using EventBusOptions and setting the reconnect-interval 
    to control how often to try reconnecting. The reconnectAttempts setting, or similar configuration
    option, determines the maximum number of reconnection attempts before giving up.
-->
<!ELEMENT reconnect-attempts (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    This setting on the Event Bus determines how long the Event Bus will wait for a connection 
    to be established before timing out. This timeout applies when a client attempts to connect
    to an Event Bus node.
-->
<!ELEMENT connect-timeout (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It allows all consumers to receive messages published to any address. This means any Verticle
    can send a message to any other Verticle without explicit trust or authorization. It's a 
    simplified approach to messaging, especially useful in development or small applications.
-->
<!ELEMENT trust-all (#PCDATA)>

<!--- Put your DTDDoc comment here. -->
<!ELEMENT log-activity (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    This setting is used to configure the behavior of the Vert.x DNS resolver. They allow you 
    to specify DNS servers, configure cache TTL, and adjust other resolver settings.
-->
<!ELEMENT address-resolver-options (hosts-path|hosts-refresh-period|servers|opt-resource-enabled|cache-min-time-to-live|cache-max-time-to-live|cache-negative-time-to-live|query-timeout|max-queries|rd-flag|search-domains|ndots|rotate-servers|round-robin-inet-address)*>

<!--- 
    Provides a way to configure the address resolution behavior, including specifying an 
    alternative hosts file. The hostsPath option allows you to point to a specific file that 
    the DNS resolver should use instead of the system's default /etc/hosts file (or its 
    equivalent on other operating systems).
-->
<!ELEMENT hosts-path EMPTY>

<!--- 
    Controls how frequently the resolver checks for updates to the /etc/hosts file (or the 
    configured hosts file). Setting it to a positive value enables periodic reloading of the 
    /etc/hosts file, allowing for dynamic updates to hostname mappings.
-->
<!ELEMENT hosts-refresh-period EMPTY>

<!--- 
    Allows you to specify a list of DNS server addresses that Vert.x will use when resolving 
    hostnames to IP addresses. This is crucial for applications that need to connect to external 
    services or other applications by domain name rather than directly by IP address.
-->
<!ELEMENT servers EMPTY>

<!--- 
    Controls whether a DNS query includes an optional resource record (OPT RR) that hints 
    to the DNS server about the resolver's capacity to handle large responses. Setting this 
    to true (the default) enables the feature, potentially improving performance by allowing 
    larger responses.
-->
<!ELEMENT opt-resource-enabled EMPTY>

<!--- 
    Specifies the minimum time in seconds that a successfully resolved DNS address will be cached. 
    This setting ensures that even if a DNS record has a very short TTL (Time To Live), the 
    resolved address will be kept in the cache for at least the specified minimum time, preventing 
    excessive DNS lookups.
-->
<!ELEMENT cache-min-time-to-live EMPTY>

<!--- 
    Controls the maximum time (in seconds) that a successfully resolved DNS address will be cached. 
    This setting helps optimize DNS lookups by avoiding repeated queries for the same address within 
    a certain timeframe.
-->
<!ELEMENT cache-max-time-to-live EMPTY>

<!--- 
    Specifies the duration (in seconds) for which failed hostname resolutions are cached. During 
    this time, subsequent attempts to resolve the same hostname will not trigger a DNS query, but 
    instead, return the cached negative result, improving performance by reducing DNS traffic and 
    speeding up responses for failed lookups.
-->
<!ELEMENT cache-negative-time-to-live EMPTY>

<!--- 
    This setting determines the maximum amount of time (in milliseconds) that the address resolver 
    will wait for a response to a DNS query before considering it a timeout. Essentially, it controls 
    how long Vert.x will wait for a DNS server to respond to a request before giving up and potentially 
    trying another server or action.
-->
<!ELEMENT query-timeout EMPTY>

<!--- 
    Allows you to configure the maximum number of queries sent during a hostname resolution.
    This is useful for managing DNS resolution behavior and potentially preventing excessive queries. 
    The default value is typically determined by the operating system or set to 1.
-->
<!ELEMENT max-queries EMPTY>

<!--- 
    It controls the "Recursion Desired" (RD) flag in DNS queries. Setting it to true (the default) 
    means the resolver will request recursive resolution from the DNS server, while false means it 
    will not. This flag influences how the DNS server handles the query and whether it attempts to
    resolve the domain name further if it doesn't have a direct answer.
-->
<!ELEMENT rd-flag EMPTY>

<!--- 
    Search domains are used when resolving hostnames that are not fully qualified (i.e., 
    they don't have a domain suffix). The resolver will append each search domain to the 
    hostname until a valid IP address is found.
-->
<!ELEMENT search-domains EMPTY>

<!--- 
    Controls how the resolver handles hostnames with dots when resolving DNS addresses using 
    search domains. Specifically, it determines the number of dots a hostname must contain 
    before the search domains are ignored and the hostname is resolved directly.
-->
<!ELEMENT ndots EMPTY>

<!--- 
    This option, when set to true, enables round-robin selection of DNS servers from the configured 
    list, distributing the load across them. This can improve DNS resolution reliability and performance 
    by avoiding reliance on a single server.
-->
<!ELEMENT rotate-servers EMPTY>

<!--- 
    It enables a round-robin selection of IP addresses when resolving a hostname to multiple addresses. 
    This means that instead of always using the first IP address returned by the DNS server, Vert.x 
    will cycle through the available IP addresses in a round-robin fashion, distributing the connection 
    load across them.
-->
<!ELEMENT round-robin-inet-address EMPTY>

<!--- 
    The vertx error handler class.
-->
<!ELEMENT error-handler (#PCDATA)>

<!--- Put your DTDDoc comment here. -->
<!ELEMENT metric-class (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    Specify the set of verticles to be registered with Vert.x runtime. 
-->
<!ELEMENT verticles (verticle)*>

<!--- 
    Verticles are chunks of code that get deployed and run by Vert.x. 
    A Vert.x instance maintains N event loop threads (where N by default is core * 2) by default.
    Standard verticles are assigned an event loop thread when they are created and the start 
    method is called with that event loop. When you call any other methods that takes a handler 
    on a core API from an event loop then Vert.x will guarantee that those handlers, when called, 
    will be executed on the same event loop.
-->
<!ELEMENT verticle (name|class|worker|threading-model|isolation-group|ha|extra-classpath|instances|worker-pool-name|worker-pool-size|max-worker-execute-time|config)*>

<!--- 
    Specify name of the verticle.
-->
<!ELEMENT name (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    The verticle class. Must be a subclass of io.vertx.core.Verticle.
-->
<!ELEMENT class (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    Determine whether a verticle is a worker verticle or not.
    A worker verticle in Vert.x is a type of verticle that executes its code on a thread from 
    a worker thread pool, rather than on the event loop. This allows worker verticles to 
    handle blocking operations without blocking the event loop, which is crucial for maintaining 
    the responsiveness of the application.
-->
<!ELEMENT worker (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    A vertical threading model is a method where a process (like an application) is divided 
    into multiple threads, and each thread handles a distinct task within the application's 
    execution.
-->
<!ELEMENT threading-model EMPTY>

<!--- 
    It relate to how verticles are deployed and potentially share resources, especially 
    classloaders. While the concept of explicit isolation groups is not a core feature in 
    Vert.x itself, verticles can be deployed in a way that effectively isolates them.
-->
<!ELEMENT isolation-group EMPTY>

<!--- 
    Indicates whether it's a high availability verticle.
-->
<!ELEMENT ha (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    When a Verticle needs to access resources beyond the libraries that are part of the main 
    Vert.x application, you use extra-classpath to provide these external dependencies during 
    deployment. This allows Verticles to use specific versions of libraries or utilize custom 
    resources.
-->
<!ELEMENT extra-classpath EMPTY>

<!--- 
    The number of instances of the verticle to instantiate in the Vert.x server. Each verticle
    instance is strictly single threaded so to scale your application across available cores 
    you might want to deploy more than one instance. If omitted a single instance will be deployed.
-->
<!ELEMENT instances (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It allows you to specify which worker pool a verticle will use when running blocking 
    or long-running code. When a worker pool name is set, the verticle will use that 
    named worker pool, otherwise, it will use the default Vert.x worker pool.
-->
<!ELEMENT worker-pool-name EMPTY>

<!---
    An alternative way to run blocking code is to use a worker verticle. A worker
    verticle is always executed with a thread from the worker pool. By default 
    blocking code is executed on the Vert.x worker pool, configured with worker-pool-size.
-->
<!ELEMENT worker-pool-size (#PCDATA)>

<!---
    Setting dictates the maximum amount of time a worker thread can be blocked before being
    interrupted. By default, this is set to 60 seconds. This setting helps prevent blocking 
    worker threads from impacting other verticles or event loops. 
-->
<!ELEMENT max-worker-execute-time (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    Specify an optional configuration file that will be read by the specific Verticle instance.
    If the Verticle starts an embedded Http server, then provide the server configuration in a 
    special file called "server.xml".

    Refer to server.dtd for more details.
-->
<!ELEMENT config (#PCDATA)>
